  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "15:20-63 Here is a list of the cities of Judah. But we do not here find Bethlehem, afterwards the city of David, and ennobled by the birth of our Lord Jesus in it. That city, which, at the best, was but little among the thousands of Judah, Mic 5:2, except that it was thus honoured, was now so little as not to be accounted one of the cities.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This district, including the towns in \"the wilderness,\" the scene of David's wanderings (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 23:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 63:1-11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " title), and of the preaching of the Baptist ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 3:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and perhaps of our Lord's temptation ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", extended from the northern limit of Judah along the Dead Sea to the Negeb; it was bounded on the west by that part of \"the mountains\" or highlands of Judah, which adjoined Bethlehem and Maon. It abounds in limestone rocks, perforated by numerous caverns, and often of fantastic shapes. It is badly supplied with water, and hence, is for the most part barren, though affording in many parts, now quite desolate, clear tokens of former cultivation. It contained only a thin population in the days of Joshua.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Jos 15:21-63. Cities of Judah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "21-63. the uttermost cities of the tribe of the children of Judah—There is given a list of cities within the tribal territory of Judah, arranged in four divisions, corresponding to the districts of which it consisted—the cities in the southern part (Jos 15:21-32), those in the lowlands (Jos 15:33-47), those in the highlands (Jos 15:48-60), and those in the desert (Jos 15:61, 62). One gets the best idea of the relative situation of these cities by looking at the map.   ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
